1
00:00:00,208 --> 00:00:02,210
[ethereal music playing]

2
00:00:05,922 --> 00:00:08,425
[TV static playing]

3
00:00:09,509 --> 00:00:11,094
[ominous music playing]

4
00:00:31,281 --> 00:00:33,283
[ominous music swells, fades]

5
00:00:37,537 --> 00:00:40,582
- [helicopter blades whirring]
- [motor whirring]

6
00:01:03,313 --> 00:01:04,147
Sir, it's no good!

7
00:01:04,731 --> 00:01:07,484
The flames have spread to the forest
in the Third District!

8
00:01:07,984 --> 00:01:10,487
Send more choppers! We need air support!

9
00:01:10,487 --> 00:01:12,864
At this rate, the whole mountain range
is gonna go up!

10
00:01:13,448 --> 00:01:16,493
Damn it all! I don't get how
it's covering so much ground!

11
00:01:16,493 --> 00:01:18,411
[panting]

12
00:01:19,537 --> 00:01:21,539
[tense music playing]

13
00:01:22,415 --> 00:01:24,501
[grunts, sighs]

14
00:01:25,085 --> 00:01:26,920
[captain panting]

15
00:01:29,506 --> 00:01:31,132
What... what's happened here?

16
00:01:38,181 --> 00:01:40,850
[firefighter 1]
The trees, they're flattened.

17
00:01:40,850 --> 00:01:43,228
[captain] My God. Did something crash?

18
00:01:43,228 --> 00:01:45,939
[firefighter 1] No, sir.
No reports of one, at least.

19
00:01:46,481 --> 00:01:48,691
[man panting, grunts]

20
00:01:49,818 --> 00:01:52,070
Where are you, Mont Blanc?
Why can't I get a signal?

21
00:01:52,070 --> 00:01:55,281
- [firefighter 1] You can't be here!
- Mont Blanc! I'm coming!

22
00:01:55,824 --> 00:01:59,119
- [firefighter 1] Professor!
- [professor grunts] Let me go!

23
00:01:59,119 --> 00:02:01,955
[firefighter 1] No, Professor!
Any closer, and you'll burn alive!

24
00:02:01,955 --> 00:02:03,957
[professor] His signal's gone dead!

25
00:02:03,957 --> 00:02:08,169
Do you know what that means?
Mont Blanc's signal has gone dead!

26
00:02:08,169 --> 00:02:10,255
[somber music playing]

27
00:02:26,396 --> 00:02:28,398
[music swells, fades]

28
00:02:32,152 --> 00:02:33,194
[silence]

29
00:02:33,194 --> 00:02:35,280
[man 2 panting, grunting]

30
00:02:39,826 --> 00:02:41,327
[explosion]

31
00:02:41,327 --> 00:02:43,413
[man 2 panting, grunting]

32
00:02:50,545 --> 00:02:51,462
[gasps]

33
00:02:52,881 --> 00:02:54,883
[shuddered breathing]

34
00:03:05,393 --> 00:03:06,311
[moans]

35
00:03:07,979 --> 00:03:10,148
[footsteps approaching]

36
00:03:11,357 --> 00:03:13,276
What's wrong, Gesicht? I heard a gasp.

37
00:03:17,155 --> 00:03:18,364
Nothing. Really.

38
00:03:18,990 --> 00:03:19,949
I'm fine, dear.

39
00:03:19,949 --> 00:03:22,410
It seems like you've been so tired lately.

40
00:03:22,410 --> 00:03:26,456
I hope you're not working too hard.
Some time off might do you good.

41
00:03:26,456 --> 00:03:29,417
[Gesicht] I'm all right. No need to fret.

42
00:03:32,420 --> 00:03:34,130
- [woman sighs]
- [door opens]

43
00:03:34,130 --> 00:03:38,092
{\an8}[reporter] <i>As you can see,
smoke is still rising from the forest</i>

44
00:03:38,092 --> 00:03:41,930
<i>a full two days later
as scattered fires continue to burn.</i>

45
00:03:42,430 --> 00:03:45,892
<i>According to on-site investigators,
the legendary robot</i>

46
00:03:45,892 --> 00:03:49,604
<i>assigned to the Swiss Forestry Service,
Mont Blanc himself,</i>

47
00:03:49,604 --> 00:03:52,982
<i>was found dismembered
within the blaze's ring of destruction.</i>

48
00:03:53,900 --> 00:03:57,487
{\an8}<i>Mont Blanc was known the world over
as a mountain guide without equal.</i>

49
00:03:58,488 --> 00:04:01,699
{\an8}<i>He was a friend to children
and experienced climbers alike.</i>

50
00:04:02,367 --> 00:04:06,996
<i>The robot was also a tireless advocate
for man's better stewardship of nature.</i>

51
00:04:08,706 --> 00:04:12,710
<i>Condolences for the beloved Mont Blanc
are pouring in from all over the globe.</i>

52
00:04:13,378 --> 00:04:14,504
{\an8}[remote beeps]

53
00:04:16,297 --> 00:04:17,298
[woman sighs]

54
00:04:20,051 --> 00:04:21,678
Yes, this is Gesicht.

55
00:04:23,846 --> 00:04:27,016
Yes. Understood. I'll be right there.

56
00:04:28,476 --> 00:04:30,311
Work call. I have to go.

57
00:04:30,311 --> 00:04:32,271
Uh, but what about your breakfast?

58
00:04:43,574 --> 00:04:44,909
- [Gesicht] Helena.
- Uh...

59
00:04:44,909 --> 00:04:46,661
Maybe I'll take some time off.

60
00:04:46,661 --> 00:04:48,579
- We could go on a trip.
- Huh?

61
00:04:49,372 --> 00:04:51,541
I should be getting more rest,
don't you think?

62
00:04:52,750 --> 00:04:55,503
You're right, but I never thought
I'd hear you say it.

63
00:04:55,503 --> 00:04:57,588
[mysterious music playing]

64
00:05:16,024 --> 00:05:19,652
[officer 1] Bernard Lanke, 42 years old,
killed in his apartment.

65
00:05:20,153 --> 00:05:22,822
Big advocate
for the International Robot Laws.

66
00:05:25,241 --> 00:05:26,451
Was he a human?

67
00:05:26,451 --> 00:05:28,202
[officer 1] Oh. Uh, yes.

68
00:05:31,914 --> 00:05:34,834
Bad way to go. Just look at him.

69
00:05:36,127 --> 00:05:37,045
Hmm?

70
00:05:41,090 --> 00:05:42,717
[inspector 1] Hey! You there!

71
00:05:44,010 --> 00:05:46,596
You can stop rooting
through my crime scene anytime.

72
00:05:46,596 --> 00:05:50,350
Actually, sir, we've been expecting him.
He's Europol's guy.

73
00:05:50,350 --> 00:05:51,517
[inspector 1] Hmm?

74
00:05:54,562 --> 00:05:56,230
- [device chimes]
- Gesicht.

75
00:05:56,230 --> 00:05:58,524
Sorry for snapping at you like that.

76
00:05:58,524 --> 00:06:02,028
I'm Inspector Wallace
with the city police. A pleasure.

77
00:06:02,028 --> 00:06:04,947
I'm sure you've noticed,
but our killer wrecked the place.

78
00:06:04,947 --> 00:06:07,742
We're trying to figure out
if anything was stolen during the attack,

79
00:06:07,742 --> 00:06:09,952
but, uh, it's gonna take us some time.

80
00:06:09,952 --> 00:06:13,414
No, I don't think robbery
was a factor at play here.

81
00:06:13,414 --> 00:06:15,625
Huh? How do you figure?

82
00:06:16,209 --> 00:06:17,877
[Gesicht] No sign of a search.

83
00:06:17,877 --> 00:06:20,379
Come on!
With this much damage, who can say?

84
00:06:20,379 --> 00:06:21,923
I can tell.

85
00:06:21,923 --> 00:06:24,092
This damage is from the attack itself.

86
00:06:26,636 --> 00:06:29,347
All right. Then tell me
what you make of this.

87
00:06:35,019 --> 00:06:37,021
[unsettling music playing]

88
00:06:41,943 --> 00:06:44,821
[Wallace] Why'd they go to the trouble
of jamming stuff into his head

89
00:06:44,821 --> 00:06:46,823
like a pair of damn horns?

90
00:06:46,823 --> 00:06:48,658
- [phone ringing]
- [inspector 2] Hmm?

91
00:06:49,325 --> 00:06:50,576
Yes. Go ahead.

92
00:06:51,577 --> 00:06:53,162
Hold on. They what?

93
00:06:55,415 --> 00:06:57,500
They're saying someone attacked
one of our checkpoints!

94
00:06:57,500 --> 00:06:59,961
[police siren wailing]

95
00:07:01,212 --> 00:07:02,922
[tires screeching]

96
00:07:12,974 --> 00:07:14,559
We need medevac! ASAP!

97
00:07:16,436 --> 00:07:18,563
[groaning, grunting]

98
00:07:18,563 --> 00:07:21,232
Did the perp attack
anybody else, constable?

99
00:07:21,774 --> 00:07:26,070
[groans] Robby, sir.
He was at the checkpoint with me.

100
00:07:26,821 --> 00:07:28,072
He's my partner.

101
00:07:29,073 --> 00:07:31,701
Like, a constable-bot, you know?

102
00:07:31,701 --> 00:07:34,203
Model PRC1332.

103
00:07:36,497 --> 00:07:38,499
[eerie music playing]

104
00:07:42,211 --> 00:07:46,215
Hard to believe that a police robot
could be destroyed so easily.

105
00:07:48,634 --> 00:07:49,886
[officer 2] Inspector!

106
00:07:50,595 --> 00:07:53,848
We got word of a male fleeing toward
the old city's redevelopment zone.

107
00:07:53,848 --> 00:07:55,183
He matches our perp.

108
00:07:55,183 --> 00:07:58,686
Twenties, wearing a red cap,
and tattoos on both arms.

109
00:07:58,686 --> 00:08:01,147
[Wallace] Well, then?
Pair up and search the place!

110
00:08:01,147 --> 00:08:02,190
[inspector 2] Huh?

111
00:08:02,190 --> 00:08:05,234
[Wallace] Hey! I said, "Pair up,"
you damn show-off!

112
00:08:06,235 --> 00:08:07,069
Oh!

113
00:08:07,612 --> 00:08:10,156
Damn it! Europol can kiss my ass!

114
00:08:10,156 --> 00:08:12,241
[mysterious music playing]

115
00:08:13,159 --> 00:08:14,494
[bird flapping]

116
00:08:19,081 --> 00:08:21,000
[bird squawking]

117
00:08:37,433 --> 00:08:39,435
[uneasy music playing]

118
00:09:16,389 --> 00:09:17,807
[tense music playing]

119
00:09:18,391 --> 00:09:19,642
[tense music swells]

120
00:09:20,226 --> 00:09:22,395
[screaming]

121
00:09:22,395 --> 00:09:23,604
[whimpering]

122
00:09:23,604 --> 00:09:25,189
[Gesicht] I suggest you calm down.

123
00:09:25,189 --> 00:09:26,566
I didn't do anything!

124
00:09:26,566 --> 00:09:29,318
That steel pipe you're holding
has traces of material

125
00:09:29,318 --> 00:09:31,028
from a destroyed constable-bot.

126
00:09:31,028 --> 00:09:33,114
[whimpering]

127
00:09:33,114 --> 00:09:36,993
[Gesicht] Ah. You're an addict
high on a drug called "noi."

128
00:09:36,993 --> 00:09:39,120
Taken about 40 minutes ago.

129
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:40,162
Sound about right?

130
00:09:40,162 --> 00:09:41,789
[junkie whimpering]

131
00:09:41,789 --> 00:09:44,208
This is the part where you tell me
who you bought it from.

132
00:09:44,208 --> 00:09:49,213
[whimpering] A guy on Karl-Heinz Street.
I only know him as Shultz, okay?

133
00:09:49,213 --> 00:09:51,424
[Gesicht] And when
did you last see Shultz?

134
00:09:52,174 --> 00:09:54,176
Uh, early this morning before 5:00.

135
00:09:54,176 --> 00:09:57,597
If the dealer's version of events
happens to line up with what you said,

136
00:09:57,597 --> 00:09:59,098
then you have an alibi.

137
00:10:00,266 --> 00:10:03,644
5:00 a.m. is around the time
that Bernard Lanke was murdered.

138
00:10:03,644 --> 00:10:05,771
Mu... murdered? What the--

139
00:10:05,771 --> 00:10:08,941
[Gesicht] If I had to guess,
you attacked the officer with that pipe

140
00:10:08,941 --> 00:10:11,360
to avoid getting collared
on a drug charge.

141
00:10:11,986 --> 00:10:15,656
After him,
you destroyed a local constable-bot.

142
00:10:16,240 --> 00:10:18,743
Now, I can read you your rights
and arrest you without incident,

143
00:10:18,743 --> 00:10:19,827
or we can do this--

144
00:10:19,827 --> 00:10:21,704
[screaming]

145
00:10:21,704 --> 00:10:22,705
[metallic clank]

146
00:10:23,998 --> 00:10:24,832
[junkie whimpers]

147
00:10:24,832 --> 00:10:25,916
[pipe clanking]

148
00:10:25,916 --> 00:10:28,002
[junkie grunts, groans]

149
00:10:29,462 --> 00:10:30,421
[gun cocks]

150
00:10:31,005 --> 00:10:32,715
[junkie] Don't shoot me! Come on, man!

151
00:10:32,715 --> 00:10:33,966
You're perfectly safe.

152
00:10:33,966 --> 00:10:36,886
This gun's only equipped
to fire non-lethal sleeping gas.

153
00:10:37,470 --> 00:10:39,889
My construction forbids
the killing of a human.

154
00:10:39,889 --> 00:10:41,766
{\an8}Like your victim,

155
00:10:41,766 --> 00:10:43,142
{\an8}I'm a robot too.

156
00:10:49,899 --> 00:10:51,567
[doorbell rings]

157
00:10:51,567 --> 00:10:53,402
[female voice] <i>Yes? Who is it?</i>

158
00:10:53,903 --> 00:10:57,531
I'm Gesicht, ma'am. A detective.
I'm here on behalf of Europol.

159
00:10:59,825 --> 00:11:01,619
[female voice] Can I help you?

160
00:11:01,619 --> 00:11:03,704
[Gesicht] You are Robby's wife, correct?

161
00:11:03,704 --> 00:11:04,705
[Robby's wife] Yes.

162
00:11:05,748 --> 00:11:07,667
I'm afraid I have some bad news.

163
00:11:07,667 --> 00:11:09,752
[lenses whirring]

164
00:11:16,050 --> 00:11:17,760
[Robby's wife] Can I offer you
a cup of tea?

165
00:11:18,260 --> 00:11:19,679
You're a robot, same as me,

166
00:11:19,679 --> 00:11:22,932
so I'm sure you'll just go through
the motions of drinking it.

167
00:11:22,932 --> 00:11:23,849
[whirring]

168
00:11:23,849 --> 00:11:25,559
By living as the humans do,

169
00:11:25,559 --> 00:11:30,481
they say we robots can upgrade our senses
or refine them. Same difference, I guess.

170
00:11:30,481 --> 00:11:31,524
[beep]

171
00:11:31,524 --> 00:11:33,776
I suppose all that is true enough.

172
00:11:34,527 --> 00:11:38,280
But I still don't understand why
drinking tea is such a comfort to them.

173
00:11:38,906 --> 00:11:41,742
Maybe it's too subtle
for an outdated model like me.

174
00:11:41,742 --> 00:11:44,203
[emotional music playing]

175
00:11:44,203 --> 00:11:48,457
I have a job.
I work as a maid for this one family.

176
00:11:48,457 --> 00:11:52,336
They have a child. A boy.
All of them humans, of course.

177
00:11:53,254 --> 00:11:57,007
The parents had adopted a dog
back before the child was even born.

178
00:11:57,591 --> 00:12:00,094
The boy and the dog grew up like siblings.

179
00:12:00,928 --> 00:12:03,931
But then, one day, the dog died.

180
00:12:09,019 --> 00:12:13,983
Would it help if I were to erase
a portion of your memory data?

181
00:12:15,568 --> 00:12:18,821
[Robby's wife] My memories of him?
Please don't.

182
00:12:25,411 --> 00:12:28,205
[man 1 groans] Whole thing's a damn mess.

183
00:12:28,205 --> 00:12:31,375
The murder victim here
is one Bernard Lanke.

184
00:12:31,375 --> 00:12:33,919
The key member
of a Robot Law advocacy group.

185
00:12:33,919 --> 00:12:35,546
[man 1] So I see.

186
00:12:36,088 --> 00:12:37,798
I'm sure there are
plenty of people out there

187
00:12:37,798 --> 00:12:41,635
with no love for a scholar
who pushed so hard for robot rights.

188
00:12:41,635 --> 00:12:44,638
The body was found
in the following condition.

189
00:12:48,017 --> 00:12:50,352
That supposed to be horns
coming out of his head or what?

190
00:12:50,352 --> 00:12:52,855
- I'm not sure.
- [clicking]

191
00:12:52,855 --> 00:12:53,773
However...

192
00:12:55,316 --> 00:12:56,400
[device whirring]

193
00:12:56,400 --> 00:12:57,860
[monitor chirping]

194
00:13:00,905 --> 00:13:03,783
- Huh?
- Huh? Don't tell me that's--

195
00:13:04,366 --> 00:13:06,410
[Gesicht] This is how
they found Mont Blanc

196
00:13:06,410 --> 00:13:08,245
right after he was destroyed.

197
00:13:08,245 --> 00:13:09,497
More horns.

198
00:13:09,497 --> 00:13:10,414
Wait a minute!

199
00:13:10,414 --> 00:13:13,959
Are you saying that whoever tore
Mont Blanc to pieces also killed Lanke?

200
00:13:14,960 --> 00:13:18,839
[Gesicht] Inflicting that level of damage
upon a robot as sturdy as Mont Blanc

201
00:13:18,839 --> 00:13:21,050
is beyond human capability.

202
00:13:21,050 --> 00:13:25,721
Also, Lanke was the only human
in his apartment at the time of his death.

203
00:13:25,721 --> 00:13:29,225
I scanned the murder scene myself
and found no other traces.

204
00:13:29,225 --> 00:13:30,893
[man 2] He was the only human in there?

205
00:13:30,893 --> 00:13:32,853
So what the hell are you suggesting?

206
00:13:32,853 --> 00:13:34,772
You know where I'm going with this.

207
00:13:34,772 --> 00:13:35,773
I do.

208
00:13:35,773 --> 00:13:38,776
The International Robot Laws, Article 13.

209
00:13:38,776 --> 00:13:41,362
No robot can harm or murder a human.

210
00:13:41,362 --> 00:13:43,572
But if... if there's a robot out there

211
00:13:43,572 --> 00:13:46,450
who's found a way
to murder human beings at will,

212
00:13:47,117 --> 00:13:50,037
then we're right back
where we were eight years ago.

213
00:13:51,372 --> 00:13:53,374
[mysterious music playing]

214
00:13:56,126 --> 00:13:58,087
[Gesicht] I'll track down
our perpetrator, sir.

215
00:13:58,087 --> 00:14:00,089
Whether our killer is human or robot,

216
00:14:00,089 --> 00:14:03,259
there's a devil inside them,
and it must be stopped.

217
00:14:10,349 --> 00:14:12,977
[professor] A strange pedestal, isn't it?

218
00:14:12,977 --> 00:14:14,061
Back in the day,

219
00:14:14,061 --> 00:14:18,941
there was talk of building a giant statue
of Mont Blanc and putting it on top.

220
00:14:18,941 --> 00:14:22,736
However, Mont Blanc let us know
he didn't much like the idea.

221
00:14:22,736 --> 00:14:26,282
He said it would be wrong
to ruin such a scenic view of the Alps

222
00:14:26,282 --> 00:14:28,534
with a needless monument like that.

223
00:14:29,743 --> 00:14:33,706
He didn't even want us to hang onto
his body once he was nonfunctional.

224
00:14:34,456 --> 00:14:37,042
"Break it up, melt it down, recycle it."

225
00:14:37,042 --> 00:14:39,962
"No point hanging onto an empty husk,"
he would say.

226
00:14:40,504 --> 00:14:44,633
I keep thinking back
to when he was still in his prime.

227
00:14:44,633 --> 00:14:48,596
[woman on speaker] <i>Mont Blanc was a hero
in the truest sense of the word.</i>

228
00:14:50,014 --> 00:14:52,433
<i>He served in the 39th Central Asian War</i>

229
00:14:52,433 --> 00:14:54,852
<i>as a key member
of the peace-keeping forces.</i>

230
00:14:56,103 --> 00:14:59,064
<i>Not only did he help restore peace
in the Kingdom of Persia</i>

231
00:14:59,064 --> 00:15:00,816
<i>after the turmoil of war,</i>

232
00:15:01,400 --> 00:15:05,029
<i>but he apprehended many terrorist cells
without any bloodshed.</i>

233
00:15:05,613 --> 00:15:07,072
<i>Without Mont Blanc,</i>

234
00:15:07,072 --> 00:15:10,242
<i>Asia could never have achieved
its current state of peace.</i>

235
00:15:11,577 --> 00:15:13,787
<i>He was a poet and a friend of nature.</i>

236
00:15:14,330 --> 00:15:18,292
<i>He enjoyed singing with the birds
and talking with the trees of the forest.</i>

237
00:15:19,376 --> 00:15:22,046
[professor] See those people
setting up his memorial?

238
00:15:22,046 --> 00:15:26,425
Volunteers, every single one,
because they loved him.

239
00:15:27,009 --> 00:15:30,387
They loved my son
from the bottom of their hearts.

240
00:15:31,388 --> 00:15:35,100
[woman on speaker] <i>Mont Blanc.
Guardian angel of the Alps.</i>

241
00:15:35,100 --> 00:15:38,145
Tens-- No, hundreds of thousands
will come.

242
00:15:38,145 --> 00:15:41,148
They'll flock to this memorial
in three days' time...

243
00:15:41,148 --> 00:15:43,859
here to grieve the passing of their hero.

244
00:15:43,859 --> 00:15:47,821
Look, Detective,
Mont Blanc's death was no accident.

245
00:15:49,365 --> 00:15:52,284
They say it was a freak tornado
that destroyed him.

246
00:15:52,284 --> 00:15:54,828
And one was reported
in the area that night

247
00:15:54,828 --> 00:15:57,748
mere moments before the fire
that burned the forest,

248
00:15:57,748 --> 00:15:59,416
but that's not what killed him.

249
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:03,379
I beg of you.
Catch whoever did this to my boy.

250
00:16:03,962 --> 00:16:08,092
Find them, and I'll beat them bloody
with my own hands!

251
00:16:08,801 --> 00:16:12,471
[woman on speaker] <i>As the pride
of Switzerland and the world at large,</i>

252
00:16:12,471 --> 00:16:14,807
<i>Mont Blanc will live on forever...</i>

253
00:16:14,807 --> 00:16:17,309
[distorted] <i>...cherished in the memories
of all who knew him.</i>

254
00:16:17,309 --> 00:16:19,228
[static playing]

255
00:16:20,646 --> 00:16:21,855
[footsteps]

256
00:16:23,774 --> 00:16:24,984
[tense music playing]

257
00:16:25,567 --> 00:16:27,653
- [explosion]
- [Gesicht gasping]

258
00:16:29,321 --> 00:16:31,323
[machine whirring]

259
00:16:34,368 --> 00:16:37,204
[man 1 on speaker] <i>Are you awake, Gesicht?
Rise and shine.</i>

260
00:16:37,955 --> 00:16:40,124
<i>That'll do it for your
scheduled maintenance today.</i>

261
00:16:40,124 --> 00:16:43,669
You have my thanks, Professor Hoffman.
So, everything normal?

262
00:16:43,669 --> 00:16:46,714
<i>Yes. There's nothing out of the ordinary.</i>

263
00:16:46,714 --> 00:16:47,631
<i>Except...</i>

264
00:16:48,215 --> 00:16:49,133
Go on.

265
00:16:49,717 --> 00:16:53,053
[Hoffman] <i>Well, most people assume
robots aren't capable of getting tired,</i>

266
00:16:53,053 --> 00:16:55,681
<i>but given how human you are
in your design,</i>

267
00:16:55,681 --> 00:16:57,349
<i>fatigue is a real possibility.</i>

268
00:16:57,349 --> 00:16:58,809
And why not?

269
00:16:58,809 --> 00:17:01,895
The human body is just a mechanism,
the same as you are.

270
00:17:01,895 --> 00:17:06,108
No mechanism, flesh or otherwise,
can avoid the perils of overwork.

271
00:17:06,108 --> 00:17:07,317
[Gesicht] Overwork?

272
00:17:08,569 --> 00:17:12,072
You've got a difficult caseload
at the moment. No doubt about that.

273
00:17:12,072 --> 00:17:14,199
I tried to watch Mont Blanc's memorial,

274
00:17:14,199 --> 00:17:18,537
but I ended up turning it off
after a while to keep myself from crying.

275
00:17:19,621 --> 00:17:21,206
There's a theory that some sort of

276
00:17:21,206 --> 00:17:25,002
internal electromagnetic wave anomaly
made him self-destruct.

277
00:17:25,586 --> 00:17:28,047
But as an expert on the subject,

278
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:30,841
I don't believe a marvel of engineering
like Mont Blanc

279
00:17:30,841 --> 00:17:34,136
could ever be taken out
by such a minor error as that.

280
00:17:35,763 --> 00:17:40,350
Destroying a robot whom everyone adored.
Do you think you can find the perpetrator?

281
00:17:43,395 --> 00:17:46,023
I'm sure that mystery
is going to prove a challenge.

282
00:17:46,899 --> 00:17:49,777
At the same time, though,
that other case you're on,

283
00:17:49,777 --> 00:17:51,653
it looks complicated too.

284
00:17:51,653 --> 00:17:53,822
The murder of Bernard Lanke.

285
00:17:53,822 --> 00:17:56,950
I watched him advocate
for robot rights on TV many a time.

286
00:17:56,950 --> 00:17:59,286
No surprise he fell afoul of someone.

287
00:17:59,995 --> 00:18:02,414
Sure, the man had a right
to defend his opinions,

288
00:18:02,414 --> 00:18:04,249
but his remarks could cut like a knife.

289
00:18:04,833 --> 00:18:07,085
He always had
an air of condescension about him.

290
00:18:07,085 --> 00:18:09,129
Not a good way to make any friends.

291
00:18:09,129 --> 00:18:12,132
If you think about it,
they're the opposite of each other.

292
00:18:12,716 --> 00:18:14,551
A robot and a human being.

293
00:18:14,551 --> 00:18:17,805
One of them had no enemies,
and the other had nothing but.

294
00:18:18,305 --> 00:18:21,183
Yeah, juggling two tough cases like that
at the same time?

295
00:18:21,183 --> 00:18:22,976
That would tire out anybody.

296
00:18:24,144 --> 00:18:26,897
Do you mind
if I ask you something, Professor?

297
00:18:26,897 --> 00:18:28,232
[Hoffman] Not at all.

298
00:18:28,232 --> 00:18:31,527
Can a human enter a room
and then commit a crime there

299
00:18:31,527 --> 00:18:33,946
without leaving
any sort of biological trace?

300
00:18:34,780 --> 00:18:36,865
In other words, organic traces so minute,

301
00:18:36,865 --> 00:18:39,326
they can't be detected
by your sensor loadout.

302
00:18:39,326 --> 00:18:41,787
- Is that what you're asking me?
- Yes.

303
00:18:41,787 --> 00:18:44,540
Uh-huh. Quite the hypothetical.

304
00:18:44,540 --> 00:18:46,667
That is gonna take some thought.

305
00:18:50,379 --> 00:18:52,589
Call it my homework for next time.

306
00:18:52,589 --> 00:18:54,174
Oh, what am I saying?

307
00:18:54,174 --> 00:18:56,218
These checkups
should be your break from work.

308
00:18:56,802 --> 00:18:58,554
No more shoptalk, all right?

309
00:19:00,305 --> 00:19:02,266
[motor whirring]

310
00:19:04,059 --> 00:19:06,770
Incidentally, I brought up the idea
with my wife

311
00:19:06,770 --> 00:19:09,064
of us maybe going on a little trip.

312
00:19:09,064 --> 00:19:10,691
[Hoffman] Well, that sounds nice.

313
00:19:10,691 --> 00:19:12,609
But she has her work to think of as well,

314
00:19:12,609 --> 00:19:14,903
so who can say
when we'll get around to it.

315
00:19:14,903 --> 00:19:16,655
Traveling is healthy.

316
00:19:16,655 --> 00:19:18,657
The data is unanimous.

317
00:19:18,657 --> 00:19:20,742
Seeing more of the world
is a great experience

318
00:19:20,742 --> 00:19:22,619
for an artificial intelligence.

319
00:19:22,619 --> 00:19:25,163
You should go somewhere
completely different, like Japan!

320
00:19:25,747 --> 00:19:26,874
Japan?

321
00:19:26,874 --> 00:19:27,791
Uh-huh!

322
00:19:27,791 --> 00:19:30,711
A member of their scientific community
invited me over there once,

323
00:19:30,711 --> 00:19:32,504
and I jumped at the chance to visit.

324
00:19:32,504 --> 00:19:35,716
Tokyo is so interesting.
So much to see and do!

325
00:19:35,716 --> 00:19:38,927
Sounds like fun.
I'll run the idea past my wife.

326
00:19:39,636 --> 00:19:41,471
Hope you don't mind my asking,

327
00:19:41,471 --> 00:19:44,516
but are you still having
that dream you told me about?

328
00:19:47,811 --> 00:19:48,687
I am.

329
00:19:48,687 --> 00:19:50,647
Oh! Not that I'm trying
to pry it out of you.

330
00:19:50,647 --> 00:19:52,107
That would be rude of me.

331
00:19:52,107 --> 00:19:55,569
But I am intrigued at the thought
of artificial minds having dreams.

332
00:19:56,278 --> 00:19:59,364
At this point, it's pretty well-accepted
within the scientific community

333
00:19:59,364 --> 00:20:02,659
that artificial intelligence
includes a subconscious element.

334
00:20:02,659 --> 00:20:07,039
Still, it's rare to encounter a robot that
has any waking memory of the dream state.

335
00:20:07,623 --> 00:20:10,584
When you feel up to it,
could you maybe tell me what you've seen?

336
00:20:10,584 --> 00:20:11,501
[Gesicht] Hmm.

337
00:20:11,501 --> 00:20:14,671
As the 20th-century psychiatrist
Sigmund Freud was known

338
00:20:14,671 --> 00:20:16,256
to occasionally say,

339
00:20:16,256 --> 00:20:19,593
"Our dreams are more than just
idle flights of the imagination."

340
00:20:19,593 --> 00:20:21,970
"Dreams are expressions of our reality."

341
00:20:40,906 --> 00:20:43,075
- [Gesicht] Excuse me, sir.
- Hmm?

342
00:20:47,204 --> 00:20:49,831
Is that a constable-bot?

343
00:20:49,831 --> 00:20:51,667
Uh-huh. Says it right there.

344
00:20:52,376 --> 00:20:55,629
Cops are done doing forensics,
so it's time to junk it.

345
00:20:56,880 --> 00:20:58,006
You're Robby.

346
00:20:58,715 --> 00:20:59,633
Hmm?

347
00:21:00,676 --> 00:21:03,553
Would you mind
if I take a quick look at him?

348
00:21:04,054 --> 00:21:05,764
Yeah, sure. Go ahead.

349
00:21:05,764 --> 00:21:08,225
If there's any parts you want,
take 'em with you.

350
00:21:08,225 --> 00:21:09,559
The body's scrap at this point.

351
00:21:09,559 --> 00:21:10,811
[Gesicht gasps]

352
00:21:10,811 --> 00:21:12,562
[static playing]

353
00:21:12,562 --> 00:21:13,939
- [Gesicht gasps]
- [static playing]

354
00:21:13,939 --> 00:21:16,817
[man muffled] 500 Zeus a body.
What do you say?

355
00:21:18,860 --> 00:21:19,903
What's the matter?

356
00:21:21,488 --> 00:21:22,447
[gasps]

357
00:21:24,700 --> 00:21:27,244
Uh, it's nothing. Nothing at all.

358
00:21:28,996 --> 00:21:30,455
Zoned out for a second.

359
00:21:35,043 --> 00:21:37,129
[Gesicht] This is
your husband's memory chip.

360
00:21:38,630 --> 00:21:41,717
Not to overstep,
but I thought you might want it.

361
00:21:42,634 --> 00:21:47,556
[Robby's wife] Oh my goodness.
This means so much to me. Thank you.

362
00:21:47,556 --> 00:21:49,975
Well then, I can see myself out.

363
00:21:51,685 --> 00:21:52,686
[Robby's wife] Wait!

364
00:21:53,270 --> 00:21:56,481
Could I trouble you to insert it, please?

365
00:21:57,858 --> 00:22:00,193
There could be painful memories on there.

366
00:22:05,365 --> 00:22:06,616
[whirring]

367
00:22:07,451 --> 00:22:10,495
The overlapping sets of memories
could cause a malfunction.

368
00:22:10,495 --> 00:22:12,831
If that happens,
I'm ejecting it right away.

369
00:22:15,083 --> 00:22:17,794
[Robby's wife] My Robby.
He's here with me.

370
00:22:19,838 --> 00:22:21,840
[lenses whirring]

371
00:22:27,763 --> 00:22:28,638
[gasps]

372
00:22:29,389 --> 00:22:32,059
- Huh?
- [whimpering]

373
00:22:32,642 --> 00:22:34,519
Ma'am, that's enough! I'm taking it out!

374
00:22:34,519 --> 00:22:38,565
His final memories are clearly
too traumatic for you! I'm ejecting it!

375
00:22:39,399 --> 00:22:41,485
- [Robby's wife] That's strange.
- Huh?

376
00:22:42,611 --> 00:22:44,237
[Robby's wife] What could it be?

377
00:22:45,447 --> 00:22:48,033
- [Gesicht] What do you see, ma'am?
- I'll display it.

378
00:22:49,034 --> 00:22:51,870
[mysterious music playing]

379
00:22:57,667 --> 00:23:02,047
Footage of Robby's partner stopping a car
at their checkpoint before the attack.

380
00:23:07,636 --> 00:23:09,513
He takes out the human cop.

381
00:23:13,683 --> 00:23:15,936
[static playing]

382
00:23:18,188 --> 00:23:19,648
[Gesicht] Please forgive me.

383
00:23:20,232 --> 00:23:22,776
Seeing that firsthand
must have been traumatic.

384
00:23:23,402 --> 00:23:25,320
I can't apologize enough.

385
00:23:25,320 --> 00:23:26,863
- [Robby's wife] It's not that.
- Hmm?

386
00:23:27,489 --> 00:23:31,451
[Robby's wife] My husband, he reacted
to the sight of the steel pipe at once.

387
00:23:31,952 --> 00:23:34,496
I could see his stun gun at the ready.

388
00:23:34,496 --> 00:23:35,747
I saw that.

389
00:23:35,747 --> 00:23:38,041
It's very unusual that a human perpetrator

390
00:23:38,041 --> 00:23:40,752
can mount a successful attack
on a constable-bot.

391
00:23:41,253 --> 00:23:43,213
There's a lot we still don't understand
about how--

392
00:23:43,213 --> 00:23:44,673
- I know why.
- [Gesicht] Hmm?

393
00:23:44,673 --> 00:23:46,341
[Robby's wife] Watch the moment again.

394
00:23:46,341 --> 00:23:48,802
[mysterious music playing]

395
00:23:49,386 --> 00:23:52,764
[Robby's wife] With this chip in me,
I can track the memory frame by frame.

396
00:23:53,473 --> 00:23:55,725
It starts when he hits Robby's partner.

397
00:23:56,309 --> 00:23:57,769
Up until this moment,

398
00:23:57,769 --> 00:24:00,772
my husband never takes his eyes off
the man with the pipe.

399
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:03,483
But as the man rushes him,

400
00:24:04,151 --> 00:24:06,945
he was distracted by something.

401
00:24:07,446 --> 00:24:08,864
There, behind him!

402
00:24:08,864 --> 00:24:11,366
That was the apartment
Lanke was murdered in!

403
00:24:11,366 --> 00:24:13,451
[mysterious music continues]

404
00:24:14,411 --> 00:24:16,037
[grunts] That shot, right there!

405
00:24:16,037 --> 00:24:17,122
[device beeps]

406
00:24:18,123 --> 00:24:20,709
- [Gesicht] What is that thing?
- I can zoom in some.

407
00:24:20,709 --> 00:24:23,503
[device chimes, beeps]

408
00:24:23,503 --> 00:24:25,547
Definitely not a bird.

409
00:24:25,547 --> 00:24:27,299
Forensics went over all the footage,

410
00:24:27,299 --> 00:24:29,634
so why was there no mention made
of this shot?

411
00:24:30,135 --> 00:24:32,554
[Robby's wife] Unless you had
the memory chip inserted,

412
00:24:32,554 --> 00:24:34,973
you'd never notice something so brief.

413
00:24:34,973 --> 00:24:39,478
My husband caught sight of this silhouette
and was able to analyze it

414
00:24:39,478 --> 00:24:41,938
during the fraction of a second
it was in view.

415
00:24:41,938 --> 00:24:43,565
It can't be a human.

416
00:24:43,565 --> 00:24:46,234
Not the way it's jumping
from one building to another.

417
00:24:46,234 --> 00:24:48,987
[Robby's wife] Yes. But, Detective...

418
00:24:49,488 --> 00:24:50,489
[Gesicht] Huh?

419
00:24:50,989 --> 00:24:52,866
...that's not a robot.

420
00:24:53,950 --> 00:24:54,910
[gasps]

421
00:25:06,922 --> 00:25:10,800
[Gesicht] <i>A murder in a room
with no trace of a human assailant.</i>

422
00:25:12,177 --> 00:25:15,138
<i>The death of a robot,
loved the world over.</i>

423
00:25:16,973 --> 00:25:18,642
<i>And horns.</i>

424
00:25:36,493 --> 00:25:38,620
- [device chirps]
- [electronic voice] <i>Identity confirmed.</i>

425
00:25:38,620 --> 00:25:40,121
<i>Please step forward.</i>

426
00:25:43,166 --> 00:25:46,294
[footsteps approaching]

427
00:25:48,547 --> 00:25:49,673
[elevator dings]

428
00:25:54,052 --> 00:25:55,262
[elevator dings]

429
00:26:10,735 --> 00:26:13,655
Says you're a robot.
That true or what, Detective?

430
00:26:13,655 --> 00:26:14,573
[Gesicht] Yes.

431
00:26:14,573 --> 00:26:17,117
[man] Well, you could've fooled me
with that face.

432
00:26:19,703 --> 00:26:22,289
The electromagnetic waves he emits
are pretty strong.

433
00:26:22,289 --> 00:26:25,041
They could scramble your AI
if you get too close to him.

434
00:26:25,041 --> 00:26:27,335
Wear this to keep you safe.

435
00:26:27,335 --> 00:26:28,712
I'm okay, thanks.

436
00:26:28,712 --> 00:26:31,381
I'm immune. They have no effect on me.

437
00:26:31,381 --> 00:26:32,299
Really?

438
00:26:32,299 --> 00:26:35,176
A very special alloy
was used in my construction.

439
00:26:35,176 --> 00:26:36,511
I'm plain on the outside though.

440
00:26:37,095 --> 00:26:40,890
All right. Your call, sir,
but stay on your guard.

441
00:26:42,350 --> 00:26:43,852
In the time he's been here,

442
00:26:43,852 --> 00:26:47,147
he's taken out four robots
who tried to engage with him.

443
00:26:48,982 --> 00:26:52,027
[metallic clattering]

444
00:26:52,027 --> 00:26:54,738
- [motor whirring]
- [air hissing]

445
00:27:03,913 --> 00:27:06,291
[robotic sinister laughter]

446
00:27:09,336 --> 00:27:10,962
[robotic voice] Like the barricade?

447
00:27:10,962 --> 00:27:13,715
It would be funny
if it weren't so desperate.

448
00:27:14,299 --> 00:27:15,633
They fear me.

449
00:27:15,633 --> 00:27:18,053
The humans threw together
that pile of junk

450
00:27:18,053 --> 00:27:21,181
so they can pretend
they're not quaking in their boots.

451
00:27:21,723 --> 00:27:24,100
[robotic sinister laugh]

452
00:27:26,436 --> 00:27:29,314
So you're Brau1589.

453
00:27:29,314 --> 00:27:31,733
[unsettling music playing]

454
00:27:36,946 --> 00:27:42,827
[Brau1589] Robot Model HRS0288,
Inspector Gesicht.

455
00:27:42,827 --> 00:27:46,581
In terms of detective AI,
you're the best there is.

456
00:27:46,581 --> 00:27:49,793
If you can discern my model,
your ID function still works.

457
00:27:49,793 --> 00:27:51,961
[Brau1589] Ah, you're sleuthing already.

458
00:27:51,961 --> 00:27:55,298
If anything,
it's more powerful than before.

459
00:27:55,298 --> 00:27:58,218
Locked away
and smashed half to hell as I am,

460
00:27:58,218 --> 00:28:02,764
I can't help but be curious
about what's happening in the world above.

461
00:28:03,473 --> 00:28:06,476
I came here today because
there's something I needed to ask you.

462
00:28:06,476 --> 00:28:07,977
[Brau1589] Let me guess.

463
00:28:07,977 --> 00:28:10,438
What went through the mind
of a certain robot

464
00:28:10,438 --> 00:28:14,025
when it murdered a human
eight years ago, right?

465
00:28:14,025 --> 00:28:15,443
[laughing]

466
00:28:17,070 --> 00:28:20,657
Robot rights scholar
Bernard Lanke was killed at home.

467
00:28:21,157 --> 00:28:22,409
I scanned the murder scene,

468
00:28:22,409 --> 00:28:25,161
but there were no traces
of another human there.

469
00:28:25,787 --> 00:28:28,039
So was the killer a human, or was it--

470
00:28:28,039 --> 00:28:29,791
[Brau1589] Or was it a robot?

471
00:28:29,791 --> 00:28:32,877
And if it was a robot,
why'd it do such a thing?

472
00:28:33,545 --> 00:28:37,841
Just between us,
the humans examined every last bit of it.

473
00:28:37,841 --> 00:28:41,428
My murderous artificial intelligence
that is.

474
00:28:41,428 --> 00:28:44,639
They were so sure
that a defect was to blame.

475
00:28:44,639 --> 00:28:45,765
But, no.

476
00:28:45,765 --> 00:28:48,309
They couldn't find
a single thing wrong with me.

477
00:28:48,309 --> 00:28:53,273
My AI passed the tests with flying colors.
No flaw in sight.

478
00:28:53,273 --> 00:28:55,233
[mysterious music playing]

479
00:28:55,233 --> 00:28:59,529
Can you imagine how terrified
the humans were when they found that out?

480
00:28:59,529 --> 00:29:03,950
That's why they keep me locked away
down here, skewered and broken.

481
00:29:03,950 --> 00:29:06,703
If they're that afraid,
they should just pull out this spear.

482
00:29:06,703 --> 00:29:08,288
That would kill me dead.

483
00:29:08,288 --> 00:29:12,459
But, alas, my human captors
are too spineless even for that.

484
00:29:12,459 --> 00:29:14,294
[Brau1589 laughing]

485
00:29:14,794 --> 00:29:16,171
[motor whirring]

486
00:29:16,171 --> 00:29:19,215
Inspector Gesicht, if you want to peek

487
00:29:19,215 --> 00:29:21,468
into the head of a robot
who's committed murder,

488
00:29:21,468 --> 00:29:25,221
all you have to do is
exchange memory chips with me.

489
00:29:25,221 --> 00:29:28,683
Who knows?
You might learn all sorts of things.

490
00:29:32,479 --> 00:29:34,481
[uneasy music playing]

491
00:29:39,277 --> 00:29:42,197
[Gesicht] Those are some printed images
of Mont Blanc's destruction

492
00:29:42,197 --> 00:29:43,948
and the Lanke murder scene.

493
00:29:44,699 --> 00:29:47,660
The horns in both of them.
What could they mean?

494
00:29:48,745 --> 00:29:51,289
[Brau1589] The ancient gods of Europe
come to mind.

495
00:29:51,789 --> 00:29:55,376
The god of death. He had horns like these.

496
00:29:55,376 --> 00:29:59,214
There was Herne the Hunter,
who took the souls of warriors.

497
00:29:59,214 --> 00:30:01,799
He was called the "Horned King."

498
00:30:01,799 --> 00:30:03,051
In Greek mythology,

499
00:30:03,051 --> 00:30:06,679
the horned king of the underworld
was Hades, of course.

500
00:30:06,679 --> 00:30:09,349
The Roman god of the dead

501
00:30:09,349 --> 00:30:11,559
was Pluto.

502
00:30:13,561 --> 00:30:14,854
A god of the dead.

503
00:30:15,980 --> 00:30:19,234
[Brau1589] Whoever did this,
they will strike again.

504
00:30:20,193 --> 00:30:23,571
Mont Blanc, one of
the most advanced robots on earth,

505
00:30:23,571 --> 00:30:26,783
was ripped apart
like he was a children's toy.

506
00:30:26,783 --> 00:30:30,203
Come on, Detective.
Do I need to spell it out for you?

507
00:30:30,203 --> 00:30:32,705
A handful of robots were created

508
00:30:32,705 --> 00:30:36,125
with the best technologies
the world had to offer.

509
00:30:36,125 --> 00:30:40,004
Robots who can also be
weapons of mass destruction.

510
00:30:40,505 --> 00:30:44,634
You already know who else is
in the crosshairs, do you not?

511
00:30:44,634 --> 00:30:48,596
There are six of them left,
present company included.

512
00:30:59,566 --> 00:31:03,361
[unsettling music playing]

513
00:31:07,323 --> 00:31:08,157
[music fades]

514
00:31:10,952 --> 00:31:12,954
[gentle piano music playing]

515
00:31:45,278 --> 00:31:46,237
[stops playing]

516
00:31:46,821 --> 00:31:48,823
[dissonant chord plays]

517
00:31:49,407 --> 00:31:50,825
I am trying to work.

518
00:31:50,825 --> 00:31:53,661
Don't just stand there in silence
like a damn mannequin.

519
00:31:54,829 --> 00:31:57,332
[man] Sorry to have entered
without your permission.

520
00:31:57,832 --> 00:31:59,918
The security seems to have been disabled.

521
00:31:59,918 --> 00:32:01,628
[man 2] Mm-hmm.

522
00:32:01,628 --> 00:32:05,340
[man 1] Given your visual impairment,
that is not safe.

523
00:32:05,340 --> 00:32:09,719
No burglar's going to tromp out
to the middle of nowhere to steal from me.

524
00:32:09,719 --> 00:32:13,598
- [man 1] But Sir Duncan, you--
- [Duncan] Enough. Are you the new butler?

525
00:32:14,182 --> 00:32:15,141
[butler] Yes, sir.

526
00:32:15,141 --> 00:32:19,062
{\an8}I'm sure the agency sent me over
another good-for-nothing.

527
00:32:19,062 --> 00:32:20,104
{\an8}You got a name?

528
00:32:20,104 --> 00:32:23,608
Yes, sir.
You can refer to me as North No.2.

529
00:32:24,150 --> 00:32:26,819
{\an8}Direction and a number. Riveting.

530
00:32:28,696 --> 00:32:32,200
The staffing agency told me
you have a military background.

531
00:32:32,200 --> 00:32:34,744
Do you care to elaborate on that?

532
00:32:34,744 --> 00:32:37,538
[North No.2] Yes, sir.
I previously served as a butler

533
00:32:37,538 --> 00:32:39,582
for the Commander-in-Chief
of the British Army

534
00:32:39,582 --> 00:32:42,502
for the entirety
of the 39th Central Asian War.

535
00:32:42,502 --> 00:32:44,879
Hmm. Butler for a soldier, eh?

536
00:32:45,505 --> 00:32:48,174
I don't imagine
you're much to look at, are you?

537
00:32:48,675 --> 00:32:51,678
[North No.2] I wear a cape
while in the presence of others.

538
00:32:51,678 --> 00:32:55,473
But of course.
Your whole damn body's a weapon.

539
00:32:56,224 --> 00:32:58,935
- Make me tea, weapon.
- [North No.2] At once, sir.

540
00:32:59,602 --> 00:33:01,187
[Duncan] As for the type...

541
00:33:01,187 --> 00:33:02,605
[North No.2] Don't worry, sir.

542
00:33:02,605 --> 00:33:05,900
I made sure to download
all of your relevant data en route.

543
00:33:08,736 --> 00:33:12,365
[grumbling]
What the hell's my "relevant data"?

544
00:33:13,700 --> 00:33:15,284
[North No.2] Prior to this assignment,

545
00:33:15,284 --> 00:33:18,246
I had the chance
to watch one of the films you worked on.

546
00:33:18,871 --> 00:33:21,874
It was the movie
<i>The Queen on the Satellite Orbit,</i>

547
00:33:21,874 --> 00:33:23,000
and I was very moved

548
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:26,504
by how the soundtrack served
to uplift the imagery.

549
00:33:26,504 --> 00:33:28,923
Is that part of your "relevant data"?

550
00:33:28,923 --> 00:33:31,759
No, sir. I was sincerely moved by it.

551
00:33:31,759 --> 00:33:35,013
That film has been out
for more than a decade now.

552
00:33:35,596 --> 00:33:36,723
[North No.2] Your tea.

553
00:33:37,765 --> 00:33:39,726
Used to call me the "blind genius"

554
00:33:39,726 --> 00:33:42,812
back when I was stacking up film awards
like cordwood.

555
00:33:42,812 --> 00:33:44,731
Every score I composed was a hit.

556
00:33:44,731 --> 00:33:47,233
I'm sure you have the more recent reviews

557
00:33:47,233 --> 00:33:50,111
rattling around
in that metal skull of yours.

558
00:33:50,778 --> 00:33:54,240
"The wellspring of Paul Duncan's talent
has run dry."

559
00:33:54,782 --> 00:33:55,867
End quote.

560
00:33:56,367 --> 00:33:57,660
The hell it has.

561
00:33:57,660 --> 00:34:01,539
I could still compose circles
around anyone if I had a mind to.

562
00:34:01,539 --> 00:34:03,875
How dare they just write me off?

563
00:34:03,875 --> 00:34:07,128
They would be on their feet,
applauding at my simplest leitmotif,

564
00:34:07,128 --> 00:34:10,882
then I'd squeeze their heart with my notes
and leave them in tears.

565
00:34:10,882 --> 00:34:14,218
It's not that I can't compose.
It's that I refuse to.

566
00:34:14,218 --> 00:34:17,096
Such trivial things hold no appeal for me.

567
00:34:17,096 --> 00:34:20,308
[North No.2] But, sir,
you were at the piano just now.

568
00:34:20,308 --> 00:34:23,019
It was a beautiful piece,
if I may be so bold.

569
00:34:24,353 --> 00:34:26,731
That one's not meant
for the celluloid brothel.

570
00:34:26,731 --> 00:34:31,068
It's a song I write only for myself.
The world can't lay claim to any of it.

571
00:34:32,987 --> 00:34:34,238
[slurps]

572
00:34:35,490 --> 00:34:38,201
- This cup of tea is much like your name.
- [North No.2] Sir?

573
00:34:38,201 --> 00:34:40,661
[Duncan] Utterly lacking flavor.

574
00:34:40,661 --> 00:34:44,290
"A beautiful piece," eh?
Don't make me laugh.

575
00:34:44,290 --> 00:34:49,629
A hunk of military hardware like you has
no right to judge the value of my art.

576
00:34:51,464 --> 00:34:53,090
My apologies, sir.

577
00:34:54,050 --> 00:34:56,052
[gentle piano music playing]

578
00:35:17,448 --> 00:35:19,951
[dissonant chord plays]

579
00:35:25,790 --> 00:35:27,542
[Duncan] How many did you kill?

580
00:35:27,542 --> 00:35:28,584
Sir?

581
00:35:29,085 --> 00:35:32,338
How many people did you kill
in the Central Asian War?

582
00:35:32,338 --> 00:35:34,549
I'm sure you can give me an exact number.

583
00:35:35,550 --> 00:35:40,221
The International Robot Laws forbid me
from harming any humans. I am incapable.

584
00:35:40,930 --> 00:35:43,683
So then, killed lots of robots,
in other words.

585
00:35:45,143 --> 00:35:46,978
What does that number come out to?

586
00:35:49,021 --> 00:35:51,232
Don't pretend as though you've lost count.

587
00:35:53,484 --> 00:35:54,527
Get out of here.

588
00:35:55,611 --> 00:35:58,906
Your demeanor's ruining
what little appetite I have.

589
00:35:59,699 --> 00:36:01,159
[North No.2] I will take my leave.

590
00:36:06,956 --> 00:36:08,666
[footsteps approaching]

591
00:36:24,140 --> 00:36:24,974
[note plays]

592
00:36:26,392 --> 00:36:27,310
[note plays]

593
00:36:27,310 --> 00:36:30,938
[Duncan] What are you doing?
You leave my piano alone, you hear me?

594
00:36:32,481 --> 00:36:34,066
[North No.2] My apologies, sir.

595
00:36:34,984 --> 00:36:36,319
When composing music,

596
00:36:36,319 --> 00:36:38,905
this instrument
is the only one you employ.

597
00:36:38,905 --> 00:36:40,698
[Duncan] Yes. What of it?

598
00:36:40,698 --> 00:36:44,368
But you have so much
cutting-edge equipment at your disposal.

599
00:36:44,368 --> 00:36:45,661
[Duncan scoffs]

600
00:36:45,661 --> 00:36:47,955
They're cutting-edge fakeries,
just like you.

601
00:36:48,664 --> 00:36:51,459
A fake violin right there
next to a fake trumpet.

602
00:36:52,043 --> 00:36:54,378
The whole damn orchestra, fake.

603
00:36:54,378 --> 00:36:58,174
Oh, dress 'em up all you want.
They're nothing more than machines.

604
00:36:59,592 --> 00:37:00,676
No, thank you.

605
00:37:00,676 --> 00:37:03,221
That's why I never had
artificial eyes put in.

606
00:37:03,221 --> 00:37:06,265
If I need a machine
to tell me what the world looks like,

607
00:37:06,265 --> 00:37:08,142
then I'd rather not see at all.

608
00:37:08,142 --> 00:37:09,977
Far better to live in the dark.

609
00:37:09,977 --> 00:37:14,440
{\an8}The only sights worth laying eyes on
already exist within my memory.

610
00:37:15,650 --> 00:37:17,902
"The sights worth laying eyes on."

611
00:37:18,569 --> 00:37:22,406
Visions of my childhood home
back when I still had my sight.

612
00:37:22,406 --> 00:37:25,576
[North No.2] During your youth, sir,
back in Bohemia.

613
00:37:26,202 --> 00:37:28,371
That another tidbit from your data?

614
00:37:28,371 --> 00:37:32,208
It's all worthless when it's just a list
within your processors.

615
00:37:32,750 --> 00:37:34,961
It was such a beautiful milieu.

616
00:37:35,461 --> 00:37:38,047
{\an8}The fields run riot with green.

617
00:37:38,547 --> 00:37:40,341
{\an8}The wind's caress.

618
00:37:40,341 --> 00:37:45,346
{\an8}And always the glow
of the gently setting sun.

619
00:37:45,346 --> 00:37:48,099
[gentle piano music playing]

620
00:37:48,099 --> 00:37:51,686
[Duncan] <i>I will turn them into music.
I must.</i>

621
00:38:13,374 --> 00:38:14,709
[dissonant chord plays]

622
00:38:16,419 --> 00:38:17,795
[device beeping]

623
00:38:40,609 --> 00:38:44,488
[Duncan moaning, humming]

624
00:38:53,748 --> 00:38:54,832
[humming fades]

625
00:38:58,627 --> 00:39:00,087
[piano notes playing]

626
00:39:07,595 --> 00:39:10,681
[Duncan] I told you not to touch my piano,
you great clod!

627
00:39:11,682 --> 00:39:13,726
Yes, you have my apologies.

628
00:39:14,560 --> 00:39:16,562
Even if you played a song to perfection,

629
00:39:16,562 --> 00:39:20,066
the notes and chords
would all be as artificial as you are.

630
00:39:21,067 --> 00:39:21,942
Sir Duncan.

631
00:39:21,942 --> 00:39:24,945
I do not mean to intrude
upon your privacy, sir,

632
00:39:24,945 --> 00:39:28,282
but I happened to notice that
you were moaning in your sleep last night.

633
00:39:28,282 --> 00:39:29,450
{\an8}Hmm?

634
00:39:29,450 --> 00:39:31,994
{\an8}[North No.2] However,
it sounded like you were humming

635
00:39:31,994 --> 00:39:33,662
{\an8}amidst the moans as well.

636
00:39:34,830 --> 00:39:35,956
I could be mistaken,

637
00:39:35,956 --> 00:39:38,959
but I think that melody,
born of your unconscious mind,

638
00:39:38,959 --> 00:39:42,213
is the missing portion of the song
you currently struggle to finish.

639
00:39:42,213 --> 00:39:45,299
It's the section where
you always stop midway.

640
00:39:47,259 --> 00:39:50,638
This is how it went, sir. More or less.

641
00:39:51,138 --> 00:39:53,057
[North No.2 playing notes]

642
00:39:53,057 --> 00:39:54,642
[Duncan] Get out of here!

643
00:39:54,642 --> 00:39:57,853
{\an8}I have no need for you,
you piece of machinery!

644
00:39:57,853 --> 00:39:59,772
{\an8}Get out of my house this instant!

645
00:39:59,772 --> 00:40:01,190
But, sir--

646
00:40:01,190 --> 00:40:04,360
I am giving you an order! Leave at once!

647
00:40:06,612 --> 00:40:07,655
Sir Duncan.

648
00:40:11,075 --> 00:40:14,120
I would like to learn to play the piano
if you will teach me.

649
00:40:14,703 --> 00:40:16,580
[grunts] What did you say?

650
00:40:16,580 --> 00:40:19,041
As you have told me numerous times,

651
00:40:19,041 --> 00:40:22,545
no matter how well I play,
it might always ring false.

652
00:40:23,212 --> 00:40:27,049
But I'd like to know
I got as close as I could.

653
00:40:27,049 --> 00:40:31,011
A weapon like you will never
play the piano, and that's final.

654
00:40:36,016 --> 00:40:38,769
[notes play]

655
00:40:40,438 --> 00:40:41,355
[Duncan] Stop it!

656
00:40:41,355 --> 00:40:44,275
How dare you sully those keys,
you tool of war?

657
00:40:44,275 --> 00:40:47,361
{\an8}You belong on a battlefield,
and you know it!

658
00:40:48,612 --> 00:40:49,780
[North No.2] You are right.

659
00:40:49,780 --> 00:40:51,782
[piano continues]

660
00:40:51,782 --> 00:40:54,743
{\an8}That is why I'd like to learn
to play the piano.

661
00:40:55,870 --> 00:40:59,707
I do not want
to belong on the battlefield.

662
00:41:03,878 --> 00:41:05,629
[boy] Mother! [panting]

663
00:41:06,422 --> 00:41:07,590
Mother!

664
00:41:07,590 --> 00:41:09,550
[panting]

665
00:41:09,550 --> 00:41:12,011
No, please! [pants]

666
00:41:12,011 --> 00:41:13,262
Where are you?

667
00:41:13,262 --> 00:41:15,473
[panting]

668
00:41:19,018 --> 00:41:21,103
[gasps] Wait for me!

669
00:41:21,103 --> 00:41:22,146
[panting]

670
00:41:23,856 --> 00:41:25,232
Whoa! [panting]

671
00:41:25,232 --> 00:41:28,235
Mother, don't leave me behind!
I'm right here!

672
00:41:28,235 --> 00:41:29,820
[grunts]

673
00:41:29,820 --> 00:41:32,114
Mother! [sobs]

674
00:41:33,365 --> 00:41:35,075
[Duncan echoes] <i>Mother!</i>

675
00:41:40,122 --> 00:41:43,083
Are you there, North No.2?
I think that you are.

676
00:41:45,628 --> 00:41:49,006
I've told you before,
don't come into my bedroom.

677
00:41:49,006 --> 00:41:50,966
[North No.2] I apologize, Sir Duncan.

678
00:41:50,966 --> 00:41:53,802
I merely wanted to inform you
that breakfast is ready.

679
00:41:57,264 --> 00:41:59,225
I could've sworn I fired you.

680
00:42:02,102 --> 00:42:03,354
Are you still there?

681
00:42:06,732 --> 00:42:09,443
- [piano notes playing]
- [grunts, groans]

682
00:42:10,236 --> 00:42:11,153
[Duncan grunts]

683
00:42:11,153 --> 00:42:13,155
[Duncan groaning]

684
00:42:13,155 --> 00:42:15,616
[Duncan] How many times must I say it?

685
00:42:18,452 --> 00:42:20,871
Don't you touch that piano! Not ever!

686
00:42:20,871 --> 00:42:23,874
Let me play for you. Please, Sir Duncan.

687
00:42:23,874 --> 00:42:26,335
I think I've gotten
a little better than before.

688
00:42:26,335 --> 00:42:28,504
"Gotten a little better," eh?

689
00:42:28,504 --> 00:42:33,217
The only improvement you can hope for is
if you turn yourself into a metronome!

690
00:42:34,176 --> 00:42:35,928
I will attempt to recreate the melody

691
00:42:35,928 --> 00:42:38,347
you keep humming in your sleep,
Sir Duncan.

692
00:42:40,849 --> 00:42:44,228
[notes playing]

693
00:42:48,107 --> 00:42:49,775
{\an8}[cane tapping]

694
00:42:51,986 --> 00:42:53,153
[clattering]

695
00:42:54,446 --> 00:42:58,284
The sounds you torture
out of that piano are not music!

696
00:42:58,284 --> 00:43:00,953
[Duncan grunting]

697
00:43:00,953 --> 00:43:02,454
Damn this piece of junk!

698
00:43:03,247 --> 00:43:05,040
"Just input the data,

699
00:43:05,040 --> 00:43:08,627
and you can create infinite melodies
with the push of a button!"

700
00:43:09,128 --> 00:43:11,505
[breathing heavily]

701
00:43:11,505 --> 00:43:15,217
That's not music at all!
It's just sounds with no heart to it!

702
00:43:16,010 --> 00:43:18,304
You will break the machines
if you continue.

703
00:43:19,054 --> 00:43:22,182
[Duncan] Oh! Trying to protect
your own kind, is that it?

704
00:43:23,017 --> 00:43:24,351
I'll ask again.

705
00:43:24,351 --> 00:43:28,188
How many of your own kind
did you destroy on the battlefield?

706
00:43:28,188 --> 00:43:29,690
[Duncan breathing heavily]

707
00:43:29,690 --> 00:43:32,151
Take off the cape,
you cast-iron hypocrite!

708
00:43:32,151 --> 00:43:34,653
Show the world
your hideous weapon of a body!

709
00:43:34,653 --> 00:43:37,573
How many did you kill? Give me the number!

710
00:43:37,573 --> 00:43:40,075
How many notches carved into your side?

711
00:43:40,075 --> 00:43:42,828
Ha! You're a docile one, aren't you?

712
00:43:42,828 --> 00:43:44,663
A weapon of mass destruction

713
00:43:44,663 --> 00:43:48,500
programmed to behave
in front of his master, is that it?

714
00:43:49,960 --> 00:43:51,253
All right, then.

715
00:43:51,253 --> 00:43:53,339
I'm going to give you some data about me

716
00:43:53,339 --> 00:43:56,675
that I guarantee isn't rolling around
in that head of yours.

717
00:43:56,675 --> 00:43:59,970
It's the reason I moan in my sleep
in the dead of night.

718
00:44:00,554 --> 00:44:02,931
The nightmare I've had for years now.

719
00:44:04,016 --> 00:44:06,935
{\an8}Not a dream,
but the life that brought me to this.

720
00:44:06,935 --> 00:44:08,562
{\an8}Truth from long ago.

721
00:44:09,063 --> 00:44:10,773
[pensive music playing]

722
00:44:10,773 --> 00:44:13,484
[Duncan] <i>The world knows me
as Paul Duncan,</i>

723
00:44:13,484 --> 00:44:16,195
<i>but my real name is Paulo Holy.</i>

724
00:44:16,195 --> 00:44:19,114
<i>I was born into poverty in Bohemia.</i>

725
00:44:19,907 --> 00:44:21,617
<i>I can't remember my father.</i>

726
00:44:21,617 --> 00:44:23,619
<i>He died when I was young.</i>

727
00:44:23,619 --> 00:44:25,704
<i>I was born with a chronic illness.</i>

728
00:44:25,704 --> 00:44:29,792
<i>And even with thick glasses,
my eyesight was always poor.</i>

729
00:44:29,792 --> 00:44:32,586
<i>Singing songs was my only joy in life.</i>

730
00:44:33,712 --> 00:44:36,090
<i>My mother, she was a beauty.</i>

731
00:44:36,090 --> 00:44:37,633
<i>Even at her most threadbare,</i>

732
00:44:37,633 --> 00:44:41,053
<i>men would turn
and watch her walk down the street.</i>

733
00:44:41,679 --> 00:44:45,599
<i>One approached her.
He was a member of the nouveau-riche.</i>

734
00:44:46,350 --> 00:44:48,894
<i>And she, my mother,</i>

735
00:44:48,894 --> 00:44:52,231
<i>fell prey to a greed
that poisoned her heart.</i>

736
00:44:54,191 --> 00:44:55,317
Sick as I was,

737
00:44:55,317 --> 00:44:57,486
she must have thought me such a burden.

738
00:44:57,486 --> 00:44:59,530
Looking back, that has to be the reason

739
00:44:59,530 --> 00:45:01,198
why she did what she did.

740
00:45:02,282 --> 00:45:05,035
The reason why
she threw her own child away!

741
00:45:06,370 --> 00:45:10,916
<i>Out of nowhere, I was shipped off
to a boarding school in England.</i>

742
00:45:11,583 --> 00:45:13,210
<i>The other boys were cruel,</i>

743
00:45:13,711 --> 00:45:17,589
<i>and a weakling such as myself
was in no place to fight back.</i>

744
00:45:18,090 --> 00:45:19,550
<i>But through the worst of it,</i>

745
00:45:19,550 --> 00:45:23,512
<i>I clung to my music studies
like a drowning man.</i>

746
00:45:24,304 --> 00:45:26,473
<i>The long nights came at a price.</i>

747
00:45:26,473 --> 00:45:29,435
<i>I soon developed a fever I couldn't shake.</i>

748
00:45:29,435 --> 00:45:32,730
<i>Even my beloved music
slipped from my grasp.</i>

749
00:45:34,606 --> 00:45:35,441
[loud thud]

750
00:45:35,441 --> 00:45:37,526
[uneasy music playing]

751
00:45:40,863 --> 00:45:44,366
<i>I was sent from hospital ward
to hospital ward,</i>

752
00:45:44,366 --> 00:45:47,035
<i>but every day saw me grow weaker.</i>

753
00:45:47,995 --> 00:45:49,830
<i>The doctors gave up on me.</i>

754
00:45:49,830 --> 00:45:52,583
<i>And through it all,
not a peep from my mother.</i>

755
00:45:54,543 --> 00:45:58,505
<i>I was dying. They knew it, and I did too.</i>

756
00:45:59,047 --> 00:46:01,842
<i>I would perish far from home,</i>

757
00:46:01,842 --> 00:46:03,927
<i>forgotten and forlorn.</i>

758
00:46:05,971 --> 00:46:09,349
<i>And that's when
a Japanese doctor walked into my room.</i>

759
00:46:09,349 --> 00:46:13,645
<i>He didn't have a license,
but lost causes were his specialty.</i>

760
00:46:14,980 --> 00:46:17,483
[doctor] I'm going to save your life,
young man.

761
00:46:18,442 --> 00:46:22,362
But there's a chance
that you go blind in the bargain.

762
00:46:22,905 --> 00:46:24,865
[uneasy music playing]

763
00:46:24,865 --> 00:46:26,158
[monitor beeping]

764
00:46:26,158 --> 00:46:28,243
[Duncan] <i>The surgery was a success.</i>

765
00:46:29,328 --> 00:46:33,373
<i>And yet,
just as the rogue doctor had predicted,</i>

766
00:46:33,373 --> 00:46:36,210
<i>my eyes grew weaker with each passing day.</i>

767
00:46:36,210 --> 00:46:38,128
<i>I knew time was running out,</i>

768
00:46:38,128 --> 00:46:41,048
<i>and there was
so much theory left to learn.</i>

769
00:46:41,048 --> 00:46:43,467
<i>I forsook everything but the music.</i>

770
00:46:44,176 --> 00:46:46,720
<i>Music was all I had left in the world.</i>

771
00:46:47,638 --> 00:46:50,015
<i>Play it again! Quickly, now!</i>

772
00:46:50,724 --> 00:46:54,520
<i>Not yet! Not yet! Not yet!</i>

773
00:46:56,104 --> 00:46:57,189
[music fades]

774
00:46:58,315 --> 00:46:59,316
<i>And then,</i>

775
00:46:59,983 --> 00:47:02,236
<i>the darkness was complete.</i>

776
00:47:04,404 --> 00:47:07,741
A few years later,
I was told my mother had died.

777
00:47:08,242 --> 00:47:12,371
Her wealthy suitor never did bother
to make an honest woman out of her.

778
00:47:12,371 --> 00:47:15,749
They told me she was alone
when the end came.

779
00:47:15,749 --> 00:47:18,043
Abandoned, as I had been.

780
00:47:18,877 --> 00:47:20,337
I worked hard!

781
00:47:20,337 --> 00:47:24,383
When his fortunes fell,
I bought her lover's castle. All of this!

782
00:47:24,383 --> 00:47:27,928
Paulo Holy had become
the genius Paul Duncan.

783
00:47:28,512 --> 00:47:33,100
I became maestro of the music world
and took this as my reward!

784
00:47:34,142 --> 00:47:35,269
Look, Mother!

785
00:47:35,269 --> 00:47:38,272
This is what you wanted, right?
All this comfort and wealth.

786
00:47:39,022 --> 00:47:41,775
You threw your child away
for the chance to have it!

787
00:47:41,775 --> 00:47:43,277
Well, here it is!

788
00:47:44,695 --> 00:47:46,238
I prevailed!

789
00:47:46,238 --> 00:47:50,200
And now, Mother, I'm going to pay homage
to all the riches you squandered.

790
00:47:50,200 --> 00:47:53,203
The beautiful hues
of the homeland you deserted!

791
00:47:53,203 --> 00:47:56,164
<i>I will take those sights
that live in my memory</i>

792
00:47:56,164 --> 00:47:57,666
<i>and paint them into song.</i>

793
00:47:57,666 --> 00:48:01,378
{\an8}I will show you priceless things
that never should have been cast aside,

794
00:48:01,378 --> 00:48:03,171
and you will know your mistake!

795
00:48:07,467 --> 00:48:10,762
Sir Duncan,
your anger towards your mother is--

796
00:48:10,762 --> 00:48:11,889
Silence!

797
00:48:14,975 --> 00:48:18,478
I'll give you high marks,
but you leave here tomorrow.

798
00:48:29,489 --> 00:48:32,576
[gentle piano music playing]

799
00:48:49,968 --> 00:48:52,846
[North No.2] <i>That is why
I'd like to learn to play the piano.</i>

800
00:48:53,347 --> 00:48:57,309
<i>I do not want
to belong on the battlefield.</i>

801
00:48:59,561 --> 00:49:01,563
[gentle piano music continues]

802
00:49:06,610 --> 00:49:08,362
- [gunfire]
- [bombs whistling]

803
00:49:08,362 --> 00:49:09,696
[explosions]

804
00:49:33,136 --> 00:49:35,097
[crackling]

805
00:49:37,099 --> 00:49:39,101
[gentle piano music continues]

806
00:49:56,410 --> 00:49:57,369
[Duncan groans]

807
00:49:57,994 --> 00:50:00,664
[Duncan] I guess
he did get a little bit better.

808
00:50:02,582 --> 00:50:03,667
[distant howling]

809
00:50:07,504 --> 00:50:08,505
[Duncan moans]

810
00:50:13,635 --> 00:50:15,637
[device whirring]

811
00:50:18,056 --> 00:50:19,057
Hmm?

812
00:50:21,476 --> 00:50:23,478
[electrical crackling]

813
00:50:25,647 --> 00:50:29,526
[Duncan] Charging his power supply
before he leaves in the morning, eh?

814
00:50:30,235 --> 00:50:31,903
Just like a machine.

815
00:50:33,238 --> 00:50:35,157
[North No.2 moaning]

816
00:50:40,912 --> 00:50:42,914
[moaning]

817
00:50:45,375 --> 00:50:47,502
Is the robot having a nightmare?

818
00:50:48,086 --> 00:50:49,796
[North No.2 moaning]

819
00:50:54,051 --> 00:50:57,971
So they can dream.
I didn't know that about you.

820
00:50:59,806 --> 00:51:01,808
[gentle piano music playing]

821
00:51:26,124 --> 00:51:30,670
"It's not that I can't compose anymore.
It's that I refuse." Yeah.

822
00:51:33,548 --> 00:51:34,382
Hey!

823
00:51:36,259 --> 00:51:37,636
North No.2.

824
00:51:39,054 --> 00:51:41,264
North No.2! Hey!

825
00:51:44,434 --> 00:51:46,937
Mmm, sounds like he really left this time.

826
00:51:52,859 --> 00:51:55,445
Maybe I can't compose anymore.

827
00:52:09,334 --> 00:52:10,335
[phone ringing]

828
00:52:10,836 --> 00:52:12,170
[phone chimes]

829
00:52:12,170 --> 00:52:14,631
How long are you going
to make me wait for him, eh?

830
00:52:14,631 --> 00:52:17,008
When is the replacement butler
going to be here?

831
00:52:17,008 --> 00:52:19,928
<i>Uh, this is Marshall
calling from MCM Pictures.</i>

832
00:52:20,470 --> 00:52:22,472
So you're just a movie guy.

833
00:52:22,472 --> 00:52:25,433
<i>You sound a bit disappointed, Sir Duncan.
Something wrong?</i>

834
00:52:25,433 --> 00:52:29,980
No, I just had to fire my butler robot
the other day, that's all.

835
00:52:30,897 --> 00:52:32,315
Well, get on with it, then.

836
00:52:32,315 --> 00:52:36,736
<i>Yes, sir. I'm calling because we'd love
to have your work in an upcoming film.</i>

837
00:52:36,736 --> 00:52:39,156
Oh. Sounds like a job offer.

838
00:52:39,156 --> 00:52:42,784
Tell me what you have in mind,
and I'll decide if it's worth my energy.

839
00:52:43,368 --> 00:52:44,911
<i>That's very kind of you, sir.</i>

840
00:52:44,911 --> 00:52:47,789
<i>Basically, we would love to license
one of your old scores</i>

841
00:52:47,789 --> 00:52:49,082
<i>for use in this project.</i>

842
00:52:49,708 --> 00:52:52,377
What? Don't you want
to use a new soundtrack?

843
00:52:52,377 --> 00:52:57,507
<i>Oh! Uh, I was of the understanding
that you had retired from composing.</i>

844
00:52:59,467 --> 00:53:00,343
[scoffs]

845
00:53:00,343 --> 00:53:02,637
Use the damn thing any way you like.

846
00:53:02,637 --> 00:53:04,347
<i>Oh! Sir Duncan, I meant no--</i>

847
00:53:06,933 --> 00:53:09,060
[automated voice]
<i>You have one new message.</i>

848
00:53:10,896 --> 00:53:12,480
[phone chimes]

849
00:53:13,106 --> 00:53:17,110
<i>Uh, Russell here, from the Planning Office
at the British Philharmonic Orchestra.</i>

850
00:53:17,652 --> 00:53:21,948
<i>We'd been in talks about perhaps mounting
one of your works for our upcoming season.</i>

851
00:53:22,532 --> 00:53:25,994
<i>Unfortunately, we're not in a position
to follow up on that.</i>

852
00:53:26,494 --> 00:53:28,079
<i>You have my apologies.</i>

853
00:53:28,079 --> 00:53:30,290
<i>I hope we get to collaborate
in the future.</i>

854
00:53:35,420 --> 00:53:38,548
[Duncan humming]

855
00:53:51,645 --> 00:53:53,271
[North No.2] <i>I think that melody</i>

856
00:53:54,105 --> 00:53:57,859
<i>is the missing portion of the song
you currently struggle to finish.</i>

857
00:53:59,319 --> 00:54:02,322
[Duncan humming]

858
00:54:07,786 --> 00:54:08,870
[humming stops]

859
00:54:22,676 --> 00:54:25,929
[gentle piano music playing]

860
00:55:19,566 --> 00:55:21,026
[piano music building]

861
00:55:31,995 --> 00:55:33,538
[piano ends, music swells]

862
00:55:33,538 --> 00:55:35,999
[gasps, breathing heavily]

863
00:55:37,208 --> 00:55:38,460
[groans]

864
00:55:38,460 --> 00:55:41,421
[dissonant chord plays]

865
00:55:42,088 --> 00:55:44,174
[grunting]

866
00:55:44,966 --> 00:55:46,426
[growling]

867
00:55:46,426 --> 00:55:47,719
[North No.2] Sir Duncan.

868
00:55:48,928 --> 00:55:51,306
I thought you'd want to know
that I am back.

869
00:55:53,183 --> 00:55:54,309
Now what?

870
00:55:54,309 --> 00:55:56,269
Didn't I tell you to get out of here?

871
00:55:56,978 --> 00:55:59,230
I did leave, as you requested.

872
00:55:59,230 --> 00:56:01,316
I went to your hometown in Bohemia.

873
00:56:02,150 --> 00:56:04,611
[Duncan] What could have possessed you
to make that trip?

874
00:56:04,611 --> 00:56:07,238
My purpose there was to archive old music.

875
00:56:08,406 --> 00:56:11,743
In the process of collecting
many folk songs from the region,

876
00:56:12,827 --> 00:56:14,162
I was able to find it.

877
00:56:14,746 --> 00:56:17,290
The melody you continue to hum
when you are asleep.

878
00:56:17,290 --> 00:56:18,833
I know how it goes.

879
00:56:20,293 --> 00:56:22,212
Please allow me to sing it for you.

880
00:56:22,212 --> 00:56:25,757
No, damn it!
Singing should be for real people only!

881
00:56:26,257 --> 00:56:29,469
Why would you try to drag
my nightmare out into the light of day?

882
00:56:29,469 --> 00:56:33,473
We don't remember everything
like you machines, and that is a blessing!

883
00:56:34,599 --> 00:56:37,602
Your dream is not a nightmare, sir.
You deserve to know that.

884
00:56:40,146 --> 00:56:44,150
To lose the dreams I have at night
would be a mercy, but yours is different.

885
00:56:44,150 --> 00:56:45,485
[sentimental music playing]

886
00:56:46,069 --> 00:56:49,572
Just as you said,
I am nothing more than a weapon.

887
00:56:50,281 --> 00:56:53,660
During my time
in the 39th Central Asian War,

888
00:56:53,660 --> 00:56:55,954
I neutralized many of the foe's units.

889
00:56:56,704 --> 00:56:57,539
No,

890
00:56:58,289 --> 00:56:59,833
I decimated them.

891
00:57:00,333 --> 00:57:02,418
Tens of thousands of my own kind.

892
00:57:03,253 --> 00:57:04,963
And those memories,

893
00:57:04,963 --> 00:57:07,882
the memories of
the countless deaths by my hand,

894
00:57:07,882 --> 00:57:11,636
my artificial intelligence
plays them back again and again.

895
00:57:13,596 --> 00:57:16,850
While in Bohemia, I met an ancient man.

896
00:57:18,017 --> 00:57:20,854
He had a wealth of knowledge
about folk songs,

897
00:57:20,854 --> 00:57:22,939
including the song in your dream.

898
00:57:23,690 --> 00:57:27,152
He said that this one young woman
in particular

899
00:57:27,152 --> 00:57:30,530
used to sing it so beautifully,
he remembers even now.

900
00:57:32,198 --> 00:57:34,033
That young woman was your mother.

901
00:57:36,369 --> 00:57:38,913
I have so much data in my mind about you.

902
00:57:39,622 --> 00:57:42,625
It includes facts about your mother
you never got to know.

903
00:57:43,376 --> 00:57:44,878
It felt that way,

904
00:57:44,878 --> 00:57:47,422
but as your chronic illness
grew more pronounced,

905
00:57:47,422 --> 00:57:49,090
she did not abandon you.

906
00:57:49,591 --> 00:57:53,011
The rich man you hated
for stealing her affections,

907
00:57:53,011 --> 00:57:56,973
she sought him out in order to fund
the treatment that saved your life.

908
00:57:57,682 --> 00:57:58,558
It's true.

909
00:57:59,100 --> 00:58:02,687
The rogue doctor who operated on you
charged an astronomical fee,

910
00:58:02,687 --> 00:58:05,064
and that was the only way
she could afford it.

911
00:58:06,524 --> 00:58:09,527
She did not throw you away
when she sent you abroad.

912
00:58:09,527 --> 00:58:12,530
In the weeks and months,
as your vision slowly dimmed,

913
00:58:13,364 --> 00:58:15,700
your mother was never far, Sir Duncan.

914
00:58:16,451 --> 00:58:20,580
Learning how much you hated her,
she couldn't bring herself to reach out.

915
00:58:20,580 --> 00:58:23,833
The divide she would have had
to repair seemed too great.

916
00:58:24,334 --> 00:58:25,960
Uh, she was there?

917
00:58:28,087 --> 00:58:30,715
{\an8}- That can't be.
- [North No.2] It's the truth.

918
00:58:31,299 --> 00:58:33,885
When you recall your childhood in Bohemia,

919
00:58:33,885 --> 00:58:36,888
isn't there a core memory
that you've forgotten about?

920
00:58:39,432 --> 00:58:41,434
The ancient villager remembered.

921
00:58:42,560 --> 00:58:45,897
You and your mother would sing
that old folk song together

922
00:58:46,481 --> 00:58:49,108
hand-in-hand until the very last note

923
00:58:49,108 --> 00:58:52,320
as the setting sun
turned the fields into gold.

924
00:58:54,489 --> 00:58:58,326
[humming melody]

925
00:59:19,597 --> 00:59:23,226
[North No.2 and Duncan's mother
humming melody]

926
00:59:32,944 --> 00:59:34,070
[Duncan] <i>Mother.</i>

927
00:59:35,738 --> 00:59:39,200
- [North No.2 continues humming]
- [Duncan crying]

928
00:59:40,618 --> 00:59:42,829
- How can I forget? [crying]
- [humming stops]

929
00:59:45,915 --> 00:59:47,292
I apologize, sir,

930
00:59:48,084 --> 00:59:49,419
for how I sang it.

931
00:59:49,419 --> 00:59:50,753
[Duncan sobbing]

932
00:59:52,297 --> 00:59:55,216
You deserve to remember
all the pieces of your dream

933
00:59:56,676 --> 00:59:58,886
as I deserve to remember mine.

934
01:00:03,224 --> 01:00:04,517
[Duncan] North No.2?

935
01:00:05,852 --> 01:00:06,686
[sniffles]

936
01:00:06,686 --> 01:00:08,438
I want you to stay.

937
01:00:08,438 --> 01:00:11,149
Don't you ever go back to the battlefield.

938
01:00:16,612 --> 01:00:19,073
Would you like me to teach you the piano?

939
01:00:22,285 --> 01:00:23,202
Yes, sir.

940
01:00:24,037 --> 01:00:26,039
[gentle piano music playing]

941
01:00:53,149 --> 01:00:55,360
[gentle piano music continues]

942
01:01:06,913 --> 01:01:08,915
[gentle piano music continues]

943
01:01:38,152 --> 01:01:40,154
[gentle piano music continues]

944
01:02:18,401 --> 01:02:19,569
[music ends]

945
01:02:25,199 --> 01:02:26,909
North No.2!

946
01:02:26,909 --> 01:02:29,287
Hey, North No.2!

947
01:02:29,787 --> 01:02:31,622
Yes, Sir Duncan. I am here.

948
01:02:32,290 --> 01:02:34,750
I've finally finished it!
Give it a listen!

949
01:02:35,543 --> 01:02:39,005
[North No.2] Yes, sir.
I would love to hear it in its entirety.

950
01:02:39,547 --> 01:02:42,341
- However...
- Hmm? What's the matter?

951
01:02:43,176 --> 01:02:46,304
I am picking up something approaching
at a high velocity.

952
01:02:46,304 --> 01:02:47,889
Uh, like what?

953
01:02:47,889 --> 01:02:51,517
Maybe one of your robot friends
finally decided to pay you a visit.

954
01:02:51,517 --> 01:02:54,854
There was an incident
up in the Alps a few days ago.

955
01:02:54,854 --> 01:02:56,481
Did you hear reports about it?

956
01:02:56,481 --> 01:02:58,733
Something up in the Alps?

957
01:02:58,733 --> 01:03:00,860
Oh, yes. I did catch a news segment

958
01:03:00,860 --> 01:03:04,530
on how that Mont Blanc robot
was destroyed by a tornado.

959
01:03:04,530 --> 01:03:05,448
What of it?

960
01:03:06,324 --> 01:03:11,162
Just now, sir, a tornado was reported
100 kilometers from our position.

961
01:03:11,162 --> 01:03:12,288
Hmm?

962
01:03:15,625 --> 01:03:17,710
[ethereal music playing]

963
01:03:17,710 --> 01:03:20,755
An unknown assailant
is on a path of direct approach.

964
01:03:22,840 --> 01:03:24,592
[Duncan moans] Hey!

965
01:03:26,260 --> 01:03:27,929
I'll return very soon.

966
01:03:28,763 --> 01:03:30,515
Wait, North No.2!

967
01:03:31,015 --> 01:03:33,017
[thunder rumbling]

968
01:03:38,940 --> 01:03:40,483
[dramatic music playing]

969
01:03:45,238 --> 01:03:46,864
[thunder rumbling]

970
01:04:02,547 --> 01:04:03,965
[Duncan] North No.2!

971
01:04:05,967 --> 01:04:07,343
Where did you go?

972
01:04:08,928 --> 01:04:10,763
[thunder rumbling]

973
01:04:11,848 --> 01:04:13,099
Come back!

974
01:04:13,099 --> 01:04:14,308
[electrical thrumming]

975
01:04:14,809 --> 01:04:17,812
[electrical crackling]

976
01:04:20,481 --> 01:04:23,359
That sound I heard just now...
What could it be?

977
01:04:23,359 --> 01:04:26,320
[electrical crackling]

978
01:04:29,365 --> 01:04:31,784
I can't tell what's going on up there!

979
01:04:31,784 --> 01:04:35,288
[electrical crackling]

980
01:04:36,289 --> 01:04:37,790
[electrical thrumming, explosion]

981
01:04:39,375 --> 01:04:40,293
An explosion.

982
01:04:40,293 --> 01:04:42,378
[thunder rumbling]

983
01:04:46,465 --> 01:04:48,676
- [North No.2 humming]
- [Duncan] Huh?

984
01:04:52,138 --> 01:04:53,222
I hear it.

985
01:04:54,765 --> 01:04:56,767
[humming continues]

986
01:05:01,314 --> 01:05:02,732
I hear him singing.

987
01:05:04,025 --> 01:05:09,196
I feel it spreading to fill the sky.

988
01:05:15,369 --> 01:05:17,538
I hear your voice, my boy.

989
01:05:20,708 --> 01:05:22,543
{\an8}[melancholy music playing]

990
01:05:22,543 --> 01:05:25,963
{\an8}You're singing our song
and with such feeling.

991
01:05:26,672 --> 01:05:28,674
[whooshing]

992
01:05:36,766 --> 01:05:39,268
Time to come back home, North No.2.

993
01:05:39,268 --> 01:05:41,687
I think that's enough singing for one day.

994
01:05:42,772 --> 01:05:44,315
Hurry on home now.

995
01:05:46,484 --> 01:05:49,236
You're going to be late
for piano practice.

996
01:06:05,962 --> 01:06:07,296
[music fades]

997
01:06:08,172 --> 01:06:10,174
[rain pattering]

998
01:06:14,971 --> 01:06:17,181
- [boy 1] It's super awesome!
- [boy 2] Really?

999
01:06:24,980 --> 01:06:26,023
[boy 3 chuckles]

1000
01:06:35,866 --> 01:06:37,785
Ah. Found a snail, did you?

1001
01:06:38,536 --> 01:06:39,453
[boy 3] I did.

1002
01:06:44,041 --> 01:06:45,710
It's very nice to meet you.

1003
01:06:47,628 --> 01:06:49,922
I believe your name is Atom, right?

1004
01:06:49,922 --> 01:06:52,007
[ethereal music playing]

1005
01:06:52,633 --> 01:06:53,467
Uh-huh.

1006
01:06:59,014 --> 01:07:00,433
[music fades]

1007
01:07:01,225 --> 01:07:03,728
{\an8}[mysterious music playing]

1008
01:09:23,159 --> 01:09:25,160
{\an8}[music fades]

